SIMPLE: throat
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Throat
<hw>Throat</hw> <pr>(thr⟦omac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>throte</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧rote</ets>, <ets>⟦thorn⟧rotu</ets>;
akin to OHG. <ets>drozza</ets>, G. <ets>drossel</ets>; cf. OFries. & D.
<ets>stort</ets>. Cf. <er>Throttle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Anat.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The part of the neck in front of,
or ventral to, the vertebral column.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Hence, the
passage through it to the stomach and lungs; the pharynx; -- sometimes
restricted to the fauces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I can vent clamor from my <qex>throat</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A contracted portion of a vessel, or of a passage
way; <as>as, the <ex>throat</ex> of a pitcher or vase</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The part of a chimney between the
gathering, or portion of the funnel which contracts in ascending, and
the flue.</def> <rj><au>Gwilt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The upper fore
corner of a boom-and-gaff sail, or of a staysail.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>That end of a gaff which is next the mast.</def> <sd>(c)</sd>
<def>The angle where the arm of an anchor is joined to the shank.</def>
<rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld> <def>The inside of a timber
knee.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The orifice of a tubular organ;
the outer end of the tube of a monopetalous corolla; the faux, or
fauces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Throat brails</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>brails
attached to the gaff close to the mast.</cd> -- <col><b>Throat
halyards</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>halyards that raise the
throat of the gaff.</cd> -- <col><b>Throat pipe</b></col>
<fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the windpipe, or trachea.</cd> -- <col><b>To
give one the lie in his throat</b></col>, <cd>to accuse one pointedly of
lying abominably.</cd> -- <col><b>To lie in one's throat</b></col>,
<cd>to lie flatly or abominably.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Throat</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Throat
<hw>Throat</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter in the
throat; to mutter; <as>as, to <ex>throat</ex> threats</as>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mow, as beans, in a direction against their
bending.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Throatband</ent>⟦br⟧
